@node "CDPlayer" "CDPlayer"
@{b}CDPlayer@{ub}

  This commodity starts the cool graphical audio CD player that is
  inbuilt in the CDTV. However, it does not really work. My commodity
  sets up a fake cdtv.device that answers all request with TRUE but
  of course, this doesn't allow you to play audio CD's. 
  
  If you want to play audio CD's, you'll need a working cdtv.device
  emulation. The only filesystem that provides one is as far as I know
  AsimCDFS. So if you're using AsimCDFS, the CDTV audio player should
  work on your system. On all other systems, it will just open and
  stay there bur you can't use it.
  
  
  Tooltypes:
  
  CX_NOFAKEDEVICE :  Set this tooltype if you're using a filesystem
                     capable of emulating the cdtv.device (i.e. AsimCDFS).
                     If this tooltype is set, my commodity won't set up
                     a fake cdtv.device.
                    
  CX_QUIET        :  Set this tooltype if you don't want the commodity
                     to display any message. This most useful for commodities
                     you want to put into your WBstartup (e.g. the ScreenSaver).                   
   
@endnode

@node "CDTVPrefs" "CDTVPrefs"
@{b}CDTVPrefs@{ub}

  This commodity will start the preferences for the CDTV. It does not
  have any other function; it's just to demonstrate how it looks on
  a real CDTV. You can configure the things but they won't be saved
  however. Press ESC to exit from the preferences screen.
  
  
  Tooltypes:
  
  CX_QUIET        :  Set this tooltype if you don't want the commodity
                     to display any message. This most useful for commodities
                     you want to put into your WBstartup (e.g. the ScreenSaver).                   
   
@endnode
                    
@node "JoyMouse" "JoyMouse"
@{b}JoyMouse@{ub}

  This commodity installs a handler that catches all joystick events
  and interprets them as mouse events. So you can move your mouse pointer
  with the joystick and start programs by pressing the fire button.
  
  On the CDTV this is a very useful program because it had no mouse by
  default. Only the remote control which acted as joystick was there.
  So companies could use this patch to allow pseudo mouse control.
  
  
  Tooltypes:
  
  CX_QUIET        :  Set this tooltype if you don't want the commodity
                     to display any message. This most useful for commodities
                     you want to put into your WBstartup (e.g. the ScreenSaver).                   
   
@endnode

@node "KeyClick" "KeyClick"
@{b}KeyClick@{ub}

  This commodity installs a handler that catches all input events
  (e.g. mouse clicks, keyboard...) and plays a small sound click then.
  I don't know if this is really useful but at least it's part of the
  CDTV and so it's here too.
  
  
  Tooltypes:
  
  CX_QUIET        :  Set this tooltype if you don't want the commodity
                     to display any message. This most useful for commodities
                     you want to put into your WBstartup (e.g. the ScreenSaver).                   
   
@endnode

@node "ScreenSaver" "ScreenSaver"
@{b}ScreenSaver@{ub}

  This commodity is from my point of view the most useful of all. It's
  the original CDTV screen saver for your standard Amiga! This screen
  saver runs in the background in every CDTV and now you can have it
  also! 
  
  You can copy this screen saver to your WBstartup and configure it
  like you want. After the specified time of no action, it'll pop up
  then and display it's cool screen with color effects.  
  
  
  Tooltypes:
  
  CX_POPUPTIME    :  Set this tooltype to the number of seconds the screen
                     saver shall wait before it pop ups. This tooltype defaults
                     to 60 seconds of inactivity if you don't set it to any
                     value.
                     
  CX_QUIET        :  Set this tooltype if you don't want the commodity
                     to display any message. This most useful for commodities
                     you want to put into your WBstartup (e.g. the ScreenSaver).                   
   
@endnode


@node "Info" "Info"
@{b}Info@{ub}

  This tool does not call any playerprefs.library functions and was
  added somehow just for fun. It uses MUI and shows the CDTV splash
  screen which unfortunately can't be called from the library.
  
  It does not have any further use.
  
  
  Tooltypes:
  
  None
     
@endnode
